5. Before that Case, Parliaments have either broken through the Rules which bind the Spiritual Court, as in the case of the Duke of Norfolk, 1 Eliz.
               1 Eliz. n. 31. where the Parliament ratified the Marriage, as lawful according to Gods Law; tho protracted and letted, by reason of certain Decrees and Canons of the Popes Law;

                  2. & 3, W. M. or else have dissolv'd a Marriage where there had been no application to Doctors Commons, as in the case of Mrs Wharton, who had been married to Mr Cambel; and yet there had been no examination of Witnesses, but what had been before the two Houses.
